  geom_histogram(binwidth = 200000L, fill = "white",
                 color = "black") + 
  xlab("Selling price of the house") + 
  ylab("Frequency") + 
  labs(title="(a)")

sqft_hist <- ggplot(data = housing, aes(x = sqft)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 500, fill = "white",
                 color = "black") + 
  xlab("Interior square footage") + 
  ylab("Frequency") + 
  labs(title="(b)")

price_hist|sqft_hist

plot(housing$price, housing$sqft)

Note: The selling price and square footage are both positively-skewed.

Model 1: Simple linear regression model

## Price as the function of sqft

m1 <- lm(price ~ sqft, data = housing)
tidy(summary(m1))
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic  p.value
##   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)  -43581.   4403.       -9.90 4.72e-23
## 2 sqft            281.      1.94    145.   0
check_model(m1)

There are violation in the assumptions. 1. I: There is no independence in the price. Houses with larger square feet are always sold at a higher price. 2. N: Data is not normal. It is positively-skewed. 3. E: Price are not distributed at each level of house square feet.

The slope coefficient _{1} is 280.624. The price increases by 280.624 dollars for each square feet increase.

Model 2: Log transformation of Price

housing <- housing %>% 
  mutate(logprice = log(price))

m2 <- lm(logprice ~ sqft, data = housing)
tidy(summary(m2))
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   term         estimate  std.error statistic p.value
##   <chr>           <dbl>      <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept) 12.2      0.00637        1917.       0
## 2 sqft         0.000399 0.00000280      142.       0
check_model(m2)

plot(housing$sqft, housing$logprice)

compare_performance(m1, m2)
## Warning: When comparing models, please note that probably not all models were fit from
##   same data.

## m2   |    lm | 19346.318 | 19370.261 | 0.483 |     0.483 |     0.379 |     0.379

The price increases by 3.987e-04 with each 1 square feet increase.
